  "questions": [
    {
      "id": "q1",
      "text": "Git worktree workflows for AI agents: How do Cursor Worktrees, Claude Code multi-branch patterns, and Copilot Workspace handle parallel AI development on separate branches? What are proven patterns for avoiding conflicts between parallel agent worktrees? What is the max safe number of parallel worktrees and how are they cleaned up?",
      "status": "partial",
      "confidence": 40,
      "key_findings": [
        {
          "text": "Claude Code has native --worktree (-w) flag. Creates worktrees at <repo>/.claude/worktrees/<name>, branches from origin/HEAD (branch named worktree-<name>). Subagents use isolation: worktree in frontmatter for automatic worktree creation. Auto-cleanup: no changes = worktree + branch removed; changes exist = user prompted to keep/remove. .worktreeinclude file copies gitignored files (like .env) to new worktrees.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S1",
            "S5"
          ],
          "iteration": 0
        },
        {
          "text": "Aether repo already has 10 active agent worktrees (agent-a09afdfa through agent-aea49f19), each on separate worktree-agent-* branches. These were created by Claude Code's subagent isolation system. This is the existing parallel development pattern in the codebase.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S6"
          ],
          "iteration": 0
        },
        {
          "text": "Cursor supports up to 8 parallel agents via git worktrees (Feb 2026). Windsurf supports 5 parallel Cascade agents via worktrees (Wave 13). This establishes the industry pattern: all major AI coding tools converged on git worktrees for parallel agent isolation.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S1"
          ],
          "iteration": 0
        },
        {
          "text": "No hard git limit on worktree count. Practical limits are RAM/CPU: ~5-6 concurrent worktrees with active builds on 32GB RAM, 10+ on 64GB. Developers find 2-4 manually trackable. Filesystem inode limits matter on ext4; XFS/ZFS preferred for high counts. Selective execution reduces overhead 60-80%.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S4"
          ],
          "iteration": 0
        },
        {
          "text": "Conflict avoidance patterns: (1) Each agent works in isolation on its own branch — conflicts handled at merge time. (2) Restrict agents to specific directories. (3) Prohibit force pushes and cross-branch modifications. (4) Use .claude/rules.md configuration guards per worktree. (5) Agent-created worktrees show 'slightly less consistent results' than human-established boundaries.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S2"
          ],
          "iteration": 0
        },
        {
          "text": "ComposioHQ agent-orchestrator is an open-source MIT-licensed orchestrator: each agent gets own worktree + branch + PR. Plugin architecture: runtime (tmux/Docker/K8s), agent (Claude Code/Codex/Aider), workspace (worktree/clone). CI failures auto-fixed with retry logic (default 2 attempts). Review comment routing back to agents. Dashboard on port 3000.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S3"
          ],
          "iteration": 0
        }
      ],
      "iterations_touched": [
        0
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "q2",
      "text": "PR-based AI coding workflows: How do production AI coding tools (Cursor, Windsurf, Claude Code, Devin, Sweep, Aider) handle branch creation, PR generation, and merge automation? What is the state of the art for AI-generated PRs with proper descriptions, test evidence, and review context? Find open-source implementations and documented real workflows.",
      "status": "partial",
      "confidence": 35,
      "key_findings": [
        {
          "text": "Claude Code GitHub Actions (anthropics/claude-code-action@v1): Full CI/CD PR workflow triggered by @claude mentions in issues/PRs. Auto-creates branches and PRs, supports skills integration, respects CLAUDE.md for coding standards. Configurable via claude_args (--max-turns, --model, --allowedTools). Supports direct API, AWS Bedrock, and Google Vertex AI backends. Auto-detects interactive vs automation mode. PR descriptions are AI-generated with 'why' focus.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S7",
            "S14"
          ],
          "iteration": 1
        },
        {
          "text": "GitHub Copilot Coding Agent: Automates branch creation (copilot/<description> naming), commit writing, PR opening, and PR description writing. Works asynchronously in ephemeral GitHub Actions environments. Single repo, single PR per task. Review comments route back to agent for iteration. 40-60% success rate on well-scoped issues. Cannot bypass branch protection (e.g., signed commits).",
          "source_ids": [
            "S8",
            "S9"
          ],
          "iteration": 1
        },
        {
          "text": "Devin Review: Auto-reviews trigger on PR open, commit push, draft-to-ready transitions, or reviewer enrollment. Confidence-based bug labeling: 'Bugs' (severe/non-severe) and 'Flags' (investigate/informational). Auto-fix generates suggested code changes in the diff view. Groups changes logically (not alphabetically), detects code moves/copies. CLI available via 'npx devin-review {pr-url}' using git worktrees. Free for regular GitHub repos.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S10",
            "S16"
          ],
          "iteration": 1
        },
        {
          "text": "OpenAI Codex (openai/codex-action@v1): GitHub Action that installs codex-cli, starts Responses API proxy, runs codex exec. Supports @codex review comments on PRs, automatic review on every PR when enabled. Jira-to-GitHub PR automation pipeline available. GPT-5.2-Codex recommended for code review accuracy. Works with both GitHub Actions and Jenkins for on-premises deployments.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S11",
            "S15"
          ],
          "iteration": 1
        },
        {
          "text": "Aider: Tight git integration with auto-commits using Conventional Commits, '(aider)' attribution suffix on author/committer. In-chat /diff, /undo, /commit, /git commands. GitHub Action (mirrajabi/aider-github-action) for issue-to-PR workflows. No built-in branch management or merge automation — operates on current branch only. Codebase map for large project navigation.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S12",
            "S17"
          ],
          "iteration": 1
        },
        {
          "text": "Sweep AI (YC S23): Originally a GitHub issue-to-PR bot — describe task in issue, Sweep plans changes, writes code, creates PR with human review gate. Open-source. Now pivoted to JetBrains AI coding assistant while maintaining GitHub workflow capabilities.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S13"
          ],
          "iteration": 1
        },
        {
          "text": "Industry convergence pattern: All major AI coding tools converged on the same workflow shape: (1) task/issue as input → PR as output, (2) AI creates branch + commits + PR description automatically, (3) human review as mandatory gate before merge, (4) CI/CD integration via GitHub Actions, (5) review comments routed back to agents for iteration, (6) CLAUDE.md/REVIEW.md instruction files for customizing agent behavior per repo.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S7",
            "S8",
            "S10",
            "S11"
          ],
          "iteration": 1
        }
      ],
      "iterations_touched": [
        1
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "q3",
      "text": "Aether architecture integration: How should Aether's existing systems map to a PR workflow? Specifically: 24 agents (builder, watcher, gatekeeper, auditor, probe), quality gates in continue-gates.md (7 mandatory gates), midden failure tracking, pheromone steering (FOCUS/REDIRECT/FEEDBACK), colony phases with task tracking. Should each phase become a PR? Should agents review each other's PRs? How does queen/colony-prime orchestrate parallel branch work? Examine existing worktree support (.claude/worktrees/agent-*).",
      "status": "partial",
      "confidence": 35,
      "key_findings": [
        {
          "text": "Aether's 7 mandatory continue gates map naturally to PR status checks: (1) Spawn Enforcement — verify parallelism, (2) Anti-Pattern — scan for known bad patterns, (3) Gatekeeper — supply chain security (conditional on package.json), (4) Auditor — code quality scoring (block if score < 60 or critical findings), (5) TDD Evidence — verify test files exist for claimed tests, (6) Runtime Verification — interactive user confirmation, (7) Flags — no unresolved blockers. Gates 1-5 and 7 are automatable as GitHub Actions checks; Gate 6 (Runtime Verification) requires interactive user input and would need adaptation for PR workflows.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S18"
          ],
          "iteration": 2
        },
        {
          "text": "No Aether agents currently use isolation: worktree in their definitions. All 24 agents run in the main repo context. Worker isolation is enforced through role-based tool restrictions: Watcher/Gatekeeper/Auditor are read-only (no Write/Edit/Bash), Builder writes only to assigned files, Probe writes only test files. This means switching to worktree-per-agent would be a new architectural pattern, not an enhancement of an existing one.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S21",
            "S22",
            "S23",
            "S24"
          ],
          "iteration": 2
        },
        {
          "text": "Build orchestration spawns workers in dependency-ordered waves: Wave 1 (no dependencies) runs in parallel via multiple Task tool calls, subsequent waves are sequential. Conditional agents (Oracle, Architect, Ambassador) spawn pre-wave. After all Builders, Watcher and Chaos are always spawned. This wave structure maps to a 'parallel PRs per wave, sequential merge between waves' pattern.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S19"
          ],
          "iteration": 2
        },
        {
          "text": "Review agents already produce structured JSON output ideal for PR comments: Watcher returns {verification_passed, issues_found[{severity, file, line, description}], quality_score 1-10}. Auditor returns {findings{critical, high, medium, low}, issues[{file, line, severity, category}], overall_score 0-100}. Gatekeeper returns {security_findings, licenses, version_pinning_gaps}. Probe returns {tests_added, coverage{lines%, branches%, functions%}, edge_cases_discovered}.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S21",
            "S22",
            "S23",
            "S24"
          ],
          "iteration": 2
        },
        {
          "text": "Colony-prime context assembly injects pheromones, QUEEN.md wisdom, instincts, research context, and skills into every worker prompt. In a PR workflow, colony-prime would need to run once per PR branch to set context, then again at merge time. The --compact mode (4K char budget) exists for context-constrained environments like CI.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S19"
          ],
          "iteration": 2
        },
        {
          "text": "Continue flow has a natural PR lifecycle mapping: continue-verify (6-phase: build, types, lint, tests, coverage, secrets) → PR CI checks; continue-gates (7 gates) → PR required status checks; continue-advance (learning extraction, instinct creation, QUEEN.md promotion) → post-merge hooks; continue-finalize (changelog, handoff) → post-merge automation. The verification loop's command resolution chain (CLAUDE.md → codebase.md → language heuristics) would need to be replicated in CI config.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S20",
            "S18"
          ],
          "iteration": 2
        },
        {
          "text": "Build failure handling has a tiered escalation model: total wave failure → halt; partial wave failure → Tier 3 (Queen respawns with different caste); Tier 3 fails → Tier 4 (ask user). In a PR model, Tier 3 would mean auto-pushing fix commits to the PR branch; Tier 4 would mean requesting human review with context. Midden tracks failures with category/source/timestamp, and auto-emits REDIRECT pheromones when a category recurs 3+ times.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S19"
          ],
          "iteration": 2
        }
      ],
      "iterations_touched": [
        2
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "q4",
      "text": "Review automation pipeline design: What should the automated review pipeline look like? Pre-merge gates (tests pass, lint clean, no antipatterns, coverage threshold), agent-based code review (watcher reviews builder's code, auditor scores quality, probe measures coverage), conflict detection and resolution strategy, merge approval criteria. Research how GitHub Actions + AI review tools (CodeRabbit, Sourcery) structure their review pipelines.",
      "status": "partial",
      "confidence": 60,
      "key_findings": [
        {
          "text": "CodeRabbit has a 4-stage PR review pipeline: (1) preprocess PR content and build context, (2) run LLM analysis, (3) post-process AI response, (4) post review as PR comments. Configurable via .coderabbit.yaml with review profiles: 'chill' (bugs and security only) vs 'assertive' (style, naming, docs, best practices). Supports one-click commit suggestions for simple fixes and 'Fix with AI' for complex changes. File-level custom instructions via path_filters and file_path_instructions.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S25",
            "S31",
            "S33"
          ],
          "iteration": 2
        },
        {
          "text": "Sourcery uses a hybrid LLM + static analysis approach: multiple specialized AI reviewers examine code from different angles, with a validation pass to reduce false positives. Tracks general code quality, security, complexity, docs, and testing. Per-function quality scores flag lowest-scoring functions. Configuration is primarily dashboard-based (not file-based like CodeRabbit). Static rule comments limited to Python and JavaScript only.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S26"
          ],
          "iteration": 2
        },
        {
          "text": "Clash (clash-sh/clash) provides pre-merge conflict detection between git worktrees via in-memory merge-tree simulation (Rust gix library). Non-destructive. Can integrate as a Claude Code PreToolUse hook running 'clash check <file>' before Write/Edit operations. Also supports 'clash status' (conflict matrix across all worktrees), 'clash watch' (live TUI), and JSON output for automation.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S28"
          ],
          "iteration": 2
        },
        {
          "text": "GitHub Actions gate aggregation uses the composite gate job pattern: a single required 'gate' job with 'needs: [lint, test, security, ...]' that runs only after all dependent jobs finish. Check suites aggregate the highest-priority conclusion from all check runs — if any single check fails, the suite reflects failure. Three successful statuses: success, skipped, neutral. All required checks must pass against the latest commit SHA before merge is allowed. For path-filtered workflows, skipped checks remain 'Pending' and block merge unless handled.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S34",
            "S35",
            "S42"
          ],
          "iteration": 3
        },
        {
          "text": "Two auto-fix commit patterns emerged in 2025-2026: (1) Direct commit — CodeRabbit's '@coderabbitai autofix' pushes fixes directly to the current PR branch as a single commit. (2) Stacked PR — '@coderabbitai autofix stacked pr' creates a separate branch off the working branch and opens an independent PR targeting it. The 4-step autofix flow: trigger (PR comment or checkbox) → collection (scan unresolved threads, gather 'Prompt for AI Agents' blocks) → generation+verification (agent applies fixes, runs build verification) → delivery (commit or stacked PR). Even if verification fails, changes are still delivered for iteration.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S38",
            "S41"
          ],
          "iteration": 3
        },
        {
          "text": "Good To Go (dsifry/goodtogo) provides deterministic PR readiness detection for AI coding agents. Classifies every PR comment as ACTIONABLE (must fix), NON_ACTIONABLE (safe to ignore: praise, nitpicks, resolved), or AMBIGUOUS (needs human judgment). Has built-in parsers for CodeRabbit, Greptile, Claude Code, and Cursor review formats. Returns one of 5 statuses: READY, ACTION_REQUIRED, UNRESOLVED, CI_FAILING, ERROR. JSON output: {status, action_items[], actionable_comments[], ci_status{}, threads{}}. Can be deployed as a GitHub Actions required status check. Supports '/rerun-gtg' comment command for re-checks without rebuilding CI.",
          "source_ids": [
            "S36",
            "S37"
          ],
          "iteration": 3
